                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d850">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 812.00/6325b.</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of State</gloss> to
                        the <gloss type="to">American Ambassador</gloss>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram—Paraphrase.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>, <lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1913-02-22T17:00:00-05:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">February 22, 1913—5 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>26. Department’s February 21, 11 p.m. In next to last paragraph the words
                    “damages to American property on account of the recent political disturbances”
                    of course refer to this whole period of disturbances.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Huntington Wilson</hi>.</signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
